<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Bezze:<BR><STRONG><BR>will have to give Zan his prop's for finally admitting it in one post back in the enchanter forum - I do take issue with his other statments about making up for it with a faster killing rate, but thats not the purpose of this post<BR></STRONG><BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Finally admitting it?  I have always admitted it    <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>I play with Dire charm in 3 ways:<P>1. Solo with a charmie<BR>2. Use a charmie in a group environment<BR>3. Use a charmie in a raid environment<P>For our purposes reviewing option 3 is of no use to this discussion.<P>If I am soloing with a Charmie then I almost always recieve 100% of the experience because I use blur/nuke.<P>If I am in a group using it, my pet generally contributes more damage than the group does.  So, lets assume, for the sake of arguement that my pet does the same amount of damage as a group.<P>Group without Dire Charm pet:<BR>  1 kill per X time interval <P>Group with Dire Charm pet:<BR>  2 kill per X time interval<P>In situation one, the group receives 100% of 1 kill worth of xp.<P>In situation two, the group receives 50 -&gt; 75% of 2 kills worth of xp depending.  In this case it will be 75% because we are equal in damage output pet vs group.<P>Hence the amount of xp is gained in the first case is less than that gained in the second where I am using a Dire charmed pet..<P>Now lets review sliding the balance in either direction a smidge.<P>Situation 1:<P>My group outdamages my pet.  In this case my group gets 100% of the xp of both mobs, which doubles the experience gained over time interval X.<P>Situation 2: <P>My pet outdamages the group.  This is a little more of a sliding scale.  The more my pet outdamages the group by the more xp he takes up to a MAXIMUM of 50%.  Correspondingly, the more my pet exceeds the group in damage output the mobs over time we are killing by using him.  Lets look at the extremes:<P>Situation 1:<BR>My pet delivers 99% of the damage to each mob and the group delivers 1% of the damage.<P>With my pet in the group the group is receiving 50% xp on 99 mobs they would not be killing and 50% xp on 1 mob they would be killing.<P>So instead of getting 100% xp on a single mob they get 50% xp on 100 mobs.  This is a net gain of 49 mobs worth of xp.<P>To the other extreme.  The pet barely out damages the group.  The group at this point is getting double the kill rate do to the presence of my pet and is receiving 75% of the xp per kill.  <P>So the group is receiving 75% of the xp on 2 mobs rather than 100% of the xp on 1 mob.  Netting a gain of half a mob worth of xp.<P>In either extreme case the group is netting more xp by using a DC pet than by not using one.<P>The reality of the situation is that the group will fall somewhere in between all the cases reviewed.  But in any case the group will gain xp faster by using a Dire Charmed pet than by not using a Dire Charmed pet.<P>The only exception to the rule which is not covered here is the case when nobody supplies any damage to the mob with the exception of the pet.<P>In this case my pet delivers 100% of the damage and takes 75% of the xp.  Of course since the group is supplying no damage whatsoever they are getting an infinite xp gain over the alternative of no xp gain for doing nothing  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>It is pretty simply math, very straight forward, not sure what you are missing here Bezze  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>Regards,<P>--------------------<P><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=65288" TARGET=_blank>Sage Zanithar TideBreaker</A><BR>Phantasmist <BR>The Relentless, Cazic Thule
</FONT>
